chttp
=====

http client to impersonate chrome browser.

Extract cookies and user-agent from browser and fake browser request using Chrome's remote debugging protocol.

Chrome must be running with remote debugging enabled:

    google-chrome --remote-debugging-port=9222 --user-data-dir=/tmp/chrome

Usage

	req, _ := http.NewRequest("GET", "https://httpbin.org/cookies")
	chttp.NewClient("ws://localhost:9222").Do(req)

Running chrome remotely

    Manually authenticate to websites using a remote X server (remmina, xpra, etc.).
    Since Chrome only allow listening on localhost, you will also need something that can forward ports, like socat, or set up iptables rules.

    Here's socat example on NixOS + tailscale.

        # 100.97.173.112:9222 (tailscale IP) -> 127.0.0.1:9222
        systemd.services."socat-9222" = {
          enable = true;

          serviceConfig = {
            ExecStart = "${pkgs.socat}/bin/socat TCP-LISTEN:9222,bind=100.97.173.112,fork TCP:127.0.0.1:9222";
          };
          wantedBy = [ "network-online.target" ];
        };

    Iptables on NixOS.

        networking.firewall.extraCommands = ''
          iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp ! -s 127.0.0.0/8 --dport 9222 -j DNAT --to-destination 127.0.0.1:9222
          iptables -t nat -A OUTPUT -p tcp -d 127.0.0.2 --dport 9222 -j DNAT --to-destination 127.0.0.1:9222
        '';

    Now you can connect to remote Chrome instance using its remote address.

	    chttp.NewClient("ws://100.97.173.112:9222").Do(req)
  
